Yesterday I installed all the programs that I need for my IT studies.
First, I set up Visual Studio Code as my main code editor.
Then I installed Python with pip, so I can run and test my scripts.
I also added Git for Windows, which I will use together with GitHub.
After that, I installed Node.js for future web projects and extensions.
I downloaded Google Chrome for practicing with DevTools.
For API testing, I installed Postman.

Finally, I added some extra tools: 7-Zip for archives and Notepad++ as a simple text editor.

Now my computer is ready for learning Python, testing, and web development.

Today I started working with GitHub. It may look like a small step, but for me it is important. 
I created my first repository, added a README file, and practiced basic commands with Git Bash. 
Now I understand better how version control works, and I feel motivated to continue learning.


I recently started working with GitHub and created my first repository for my profile.
In this repository I added a README.md file, where I described my background, skills, and future IT goals.

I practiced different ways to work with GitHub:

First, I created and uploaded files directly on the GitHub website.

Second, I used Git Bash to clone the repository to my computer. Then I added my README.md file, made a commit with a message, and pushed it back to GitHub.

I also learned how to open the Windows Command Line using Win + R â†’ cmd. With the command line I can move between folders and run git commands.

This experience helped me understand how version control works in real life. Now I know the basic steps: clone â†’ add â†’ commit â†’ push.
It was my first practice, but it gave me more confidence to continue learning Git, GitHub, and programming.



Repository (repo)
A storage for your project on GitHub.
ðŸ‘‰ Used on: GitHub website, Git Bash

Clone
Copy a remote repository from GitHub to your local computer.                   (git clone)

Add
Put changed or new files into the staging area before saving them.             (git add README.md)

Commit
Save the current state of your project with a message.                         (git commit -m "message")

Push
Send your commits from the local repository to GitHub.                         (git push origin main)

Pull
Get updates from GitHub to your computer.                                      (git pull)

Branch
A parallel version of your project. The main one is usually called main or master.
ðŸ‘‰ Used on: GitHub website, Git Bash

README.md
A Markdown file that describes your project or profile. It is shown on the front page of your repository.
ðŸ‘‰ Used on: GitHub website, Git Bash, any text editor (VS Code, Notepad)

Markdown (.md)
A simple format for text with headers, links, lists, and code blocks.
ðŸ‘‰ Used on: README.md file (VS Code, GitHub website)

Command Line (CMD)
A Windows program to type and run commands. Open with Win + R â†’ cmd.
ðŸ‘‰ Used on: Windows CMD

Git Bash
A terminal program for running Git commands on Windows.
ðŸ‘‰ Used on: Git Bash

